commit.message:
fixed README

- removed a broken and unused link anchor
- fixed an invalid link to the example shoot manifest

added modular seed configuration

It is now possible to deploy several seeds on the cluster. There are several ways to do this:

1. On "deploy_gardener.sh", all seeds that are listed in seed_config.seeds in the landscape.yaml
are automatically deployed. On "undeploy_gardener.sh", all possible seeds are deleted to clean up
seed that were added manually (see below) and not leave any resources behind.

2. The seed-config deploy script now takes seeds as arguments. To create a seed, go to the
components folder and call './deploy.sh seed-config <seed>'. It is possible to provide multiple
seed arguments to create several seeds at once. If no arguments are given, the script uses the
seeds specified in the landscape.yaml, see above. Only the specified seeds are created, already
existing other seeds are not affected. This works the same way when the "-u"/"--uninstall" option
is given. The order of the arguments is not relevant.

Valid values for seeds are "aws", "az" (for Azure), "gcp", and "openstack". For every seed the
corresponding variants in the authentication and seed-config nodes in landscape.yaml have to exist
and be filled out.

Please note that while it is possible to create seeds for any cloud provider on any cloud provider,
actual shoot creation may not always work across the cloud providers. For example, creating an Azure
shoot from a seed on AWS works without problems, but creating a GCP shoot doesn't right now.

adapted aliases and added bash completion

The following aliases can now be used within the docker images:
k => kubectl
ks => kubectl -n kube-system
kg => kubectl -n garden
kn => kubectl -n
ka => kubectl get --all-namespaces

Bash completion will work for all except the "ka" alias.

added automation for sessionAffinity fix

At the end of the deploy_kubify.sh script, the kubernetes service will
automatically be patched to apply the workaround for the sessionAffinity
problem.
added information on letsencrypt rate limits to README
added workaround for certmanager crash (and other problems) to readme

Split of README

To keep the documentation close to the corresponding code,
the readme has been splitted. One part, describing the project in general,
remains in the landscape-setup-template project.
The other part, describing the installation procedure, is moved into this project
as it describes the usage of the scripts located in this project.
